WEBVTT

00:13.542 --> 00:15.584
(car door closes)

00:15.667 --> 00:17.125
(engine starts)

00:19.334 --> 00:23.167
(intense digital music playing)

00:27.292 --> 00:30.000
Scott Wapner:
<i>He started from nothing</i>
<i>and built a fortune</i>

00:30.083 --> 00:32.667
<i>worth upwards
of $20 billion.</i>

00:32.751 --> 00:34.918
♪ ♪

00:39.042 --> 00:41.042
reporter:<i> It is not often</i>
<i>that a Wall Street titan</i>

00:41.125 --> 00:44.918
<i>shows up on the cover
of "Time" magazine.</i>

00:45.000 --> 00:47.292
reporter 2:<i> The most feared</i>
<i>corporate raider in the world.</i>

00:47.375 --> 00:49.292
reporter 3:
<i>One of the shrewdest</i>
<i>investors on the planet.</i>

00:49.375 --> 00:50.626
reporter 4:
<i>He moves markets</i>

00:50.709 --> 00:52.042
<i>by the mere
mention of his name.</i>

00:52.125 --> 00:53.751
reporter 5:
<i>"Fortune" magazine says</i>

00:53.834 --> 00:55.959
<i>he may be making
more money for shareholders</i>

00:56.042 --> 00:58.125
<i>than anyone else on the planet.</i>

00:59.375 --> 01:01.834
(applause)

01:01.918 --> 01:03.834
Gail Golden-Icahn:
<i>He's tenacious.</i>

01:03.918 --> 01:06.375
-man 1:<i> Enigma.</i>
-man 2:<i> The smartest guy</i>
<i>I've ever met.</i>

01:06.459 --> 01:08.500
woman:
<i>He's the great white shark</i>

01:08.584 --> 01:11.375
<i>in the sea of capitalism.</i>

01:11.459 --> 01:14.751
Carl Icahn:<i> My mother said</i>
<i>I have some kind of warrior</i>
<i>gene in me or something.</i>

01:14.834 --> 01:16.209
interviewer:
<i>A warrior gene?</i>

01:18.167 --> 01:21.042
various voices:
<i>Marvel Comics, Time Warner,</i>
<i>Texaco, US Steel,</i>

01:21.125 --> 01:24.459
<i>Dell Computers,
Apple, PayPal, Caesars.</i>

01:24.542 --> 01:26.417
reporter:<i> Motorola. Yahoo...</i>
<i>all have felt</i>

01:26.500 --> 01:28.792
<i>the pointed sting
of Carl Icahn.</i>

01:28.876 --> 01:31.584
I do it because
in a free enterprise system,
I do it for profit,

01:31.667 --> 01:33.000
but what I do should be done.

01:33.083 --> 01:34.751
-Totally terrifying.
-Bully.

01:34.834 --> 01:37.834
Great guy, but he's about
as smooth as a stucco bathtub.

01:37.918 --> 01:39.334
I own it, it's my money.

01:39.417 --> 01:41.584
If I lose, I'm answerable
to my bank account.

01:41.667 --> 01:43.959
♪ ♪

01:44.042 --> 01:47.918
I'm 85, you say, this guy's 85.
Pretty good, right?

01:48.000 --> 01:49.667
I can get some real heat on 'em.

01:53.209 --> 01:54.792
<i>I don't like to start wars,</i>

01:54.876 --> 01:56.459
<i>but if somebody wants
to start it with me,</i>

01:56.542 --> 01:58.209
<i>there's something in me
that likes that</i>

01:58.292 --> 02:00.667
<i>'cause I'm really looking
forward to going at 'em.</i>

02:00.751 --> 02:03.918
♪ ♪

02:08.626 --> 02:12.417
Wall Street, they look
at Carl Icahn and they say

02:12.500 --> 02:14.334
legend, they say genius.

02:14.417 --> 02:16.042
There's an admiration

02:16.125 --> 02:18.959
for what he's been able
to accomplish

02:19.042 --> 02:20.792
and the wealth
that he's created.

02:25.250 --> 02:28.584
The public, I think,
has a much more mixed view

02:28.667 --> 02:32.292
about the impact he's had
on companies,

02:32.375 --> 02:35.167
on labor, on society.

02:35.250 --> 02:38.083
♪ ♪

02:38.167 --> 02:40.209
<i>Then the question is</i>

02:40.292 --> 02:44.334
<i>whether he is
a activist investor,</i>

02:44.417 --> 02:46.500
<i>an advocate
for the shareholder,</i>

02:46.584 --> 02:49.542
<i>representing the little guy,</i>

02:49.626 --> 02:52.626
<i>or corporate raider
who goes in,</i>

02:52.709 --> 02:56.334
<i>extracts value
out of that company</i>

02:56.417 --> 02:59.709
<i>to the detriment
of the long-term company</i>

02:59.792 --> 03:02.417
but to the immediate benefit
of Carl Icahn.

03:02.500 --> 03:05.584
Let me do it.
No, I wouldn't say it that way.

03:05.667 --> 03:08.584
It's sort of a colorful term,
"corporate raider,"

03:08.667 --> 03:10.542
but it's far from the truth.

03:10.626 --> 03:14.542
Absolutely is ridiculous
related to what we do.

03:14.626 --> 03:16.375
It's the opposite of what we do.

03:16.459 --> 03:17.792
We bring things to the party.

03:17.876 --> 03:19.542
We don't raid 'em
and take 'em out.

03:19.626 --> 03:23.334
That's why I think eventually
it was changed to "activist."

03:23.417 --> 03:25.292
But activist or raider,

03:25.375 --> 03:27.709
I haven't changed
what I do one iota.

03:27.792 --> 03:30.167
Call me whatever you want.
(chuckles)

03:31.709 --> 03:33.792
♪ ♪

03:46.667 --> 03:48.459
So, how are my boys?

03:48.542 --> 03:50.626
Ah, what good boys.

03:50.709 --> 03:52.083
Susan Gordon:
<i>He gets up about nine o'clock</i>

03:52.167 --> 03:54.334
and he's already,
he's eating his breakfast

03:54.417 --> 03:57.250
and reading the newspaper
while he's talking,

03:57.334 --> 04:00.626
and, you know, writing notes
and all that.

04:00.709 --> 04:03.167
<i>He immediately starts his day,</i>

04:03.250 --> 04:06.876
<i>catches up
with what the news is,
how the market's doing.</i>

04:06.959 --> 04:09.918
Uber's got
one thing after another.

04:10.000 --> 04:11.792
We work together
in his home office,

04:11.876 --> 04:15.209
and then, about four o'clock
in the afternoon,

04:15.292 --> 04:19.292
<i>he starts heading over
to his "office office"</i>

04:19.375 --> 04:21.542
<i>on Fifth Avenue,</i>

04:21.626 --> 04:25.626
<i>for meetings, or what
current crisis is going on.</i>

04:25.709 --> 04:28.417
Crisis manager.
I'm like Ray Donovan.

04:28.500 --> 04:31.375
I try to... I try to...
I try to get it done

04:31.459 --> 04:32.834
and then I go
into another crisis.

04:32.918 --> 04:34.209
There's always a few of 'em.

04:34.292 --> 04:36.375
<i>You don't have to
manufacture 'em.</i>

04:38.375 --> 04:41.167
Wapner:<i> I think the way</i>
<i>Carl looks at business</i>

04:41.250 --> 04:44.459
and the way he does things
is he tries to identify
companies

04:44.542 --> 04:46.209
that he thinks are undervalued,

04:46.292 --> 04:48.751
and he'll secretly build
a position

04:48.834 --> 04:53.626
until it gets large enough that
he has to reveal the size.

04:53.709 --> 04:57.000
<i>And he'll try and put pressure
on the CEO to do what he wants,</i>

04:57.083 --> 04:59.542
whether that's doing a merger
or a share buyback.

05:00.959 --> 05:05.083
<i>And in more cases than not,
over the years,</i>

05:05.167 --> 05:09.042
the CEO will end up doing
something that he wants

05:09.125 --> 05:12.334
and the stock price will go up
and Carl will make
a lot of money.

05:12.417 --> 05:16.209
Meissonier's, it's "Napoleon
at the Battle of Friedland."

05:18.083 --> 05:20.667
Before hubris took over

05:20.751 --> 05:22.584
and took it all away from him.

05:22.667 --> 05:25.667
He was one of... Well, he was
a great strategist, no question.

05:27.417 --> 05:30.834
But then he lost it all
because of his arrogance.

05:30.918 --> 05:33.042
And that's one thing
you have to remember.

05:35.834 --> 05:38.083
It doesn't stay forever
if you're not careful.

05:38.167 --> 05:41.959
(discordant percussive
music playing)

06:00.959 --> 06:04.292
(intense digital music
playing)

06:04.375 --> 06:06.959
reporter:<i> Carl Icahn, I guess,</i>
<i>doing what Carl Icahn does,</i>

06:07.042 --> 06:09.000
<i>and he is on the attack.</i>

06:09.083 --> 06:12.959
reporter 2:<i> Carl, what do you</i>
<i>object to most strongly?</i>

06:14.292 --> 06:16.042
Carl:
<i>I object to the fact</i>

06:16.125 --> 06:18.125
<i>that they did a acquisition</i>

06:18.209 --> 06:19.876
<i>that puts the company at risk</i>

06:19.959 --> 06:22.375
<i>and didn't go to the board
members for a vote.</i>

06:29.375 --> 06:31.250
Andrew Langham: Somebody
from Reuters just called.

06:31.334 --> 06:34.959
-What did they say?
-They want to understand
what we're doing.

06:35.042 --> 06:39.334
You know, we want to remove
some of the directors
and put us in.

06:39.417 --> 06:42.083
They know I'm not going away,
so we just,

06:42.167 --> 06:44.042
we just keep,
we keep going.

06:44.125 --> 06:46.792
The idea of an activist investor

06:46.876 --> 06:49.125
is they buy a stake
in a company

06:49.209 --> 06:51.000
with the plan and ambition

06:51.083 --> 06:53.834
to go to the company's
management and board and say,

06:53.918 --> 06:56.250
"You're doing it wrong.
Here's how to do it."

06:56.334 --> 06:58.918
Carl:
Yeah, how you doing?

06:59.000 --> 07:01.000
I don't have to tell you
anything you don't know.

07:01.083 --> 07:03.125
I mean, I think it was
reprehensible what went on.

07:03.209 --> 07:06.167
I think they got no right
to do that without talking
to the shareholders.

07:06.250 --> 07:08.626
You know,
they're betting the company,
it's not their money.

07:08.709 --> 07:11.626
He looks at boards
and he looks at CEOs

07:11.709 --> 07:13.000
as country club boards.

07:13.083 --> 07:15.167
They spend no time thinking
about the company.

07:15.250 --> 07:18.375
They're collecting their fee
and they're playing golf
all day.

07:18.459 --> 07:20.834
Andrew Ross Sorkin:
<i>The board of directors</i>
<i>of a company</i>

07:20.918 --> 07:22.751
<i>are supposed to represent</i>

07:22.834 --> 07:25.459
<i>the interests
of the shareholders.</i>

07:25.542 --> 07:27.375
They are supposed to hold

07:27.459 --> 07:30.709
the CEO and management
to account.

07:30.792 --> 07:32.751
That is their job.

07:32.834 --> 07:37.584
Whether they do it is
Carl Icahn's biggest question.

07:37.667 --> 07:40.083
(percussive music playing)

07:42.751 --> 07:45.167
Hey, who the hell put this out?

07:45.250 --> 07:48.042
Who got this out, that we're
replacing four directors?

07:48.125 --> 07:49.918
-Yeah.
-We just told them that.

07:50.000 --> 07:52.292
You told them
'cause I told you.
We filed it, and so...

07:52.375 --> 07:56.042
(laughs) Oh, yes, we filed.
This is what he just filed.

07:56.125 --> 07:59.250
That's just what we was talking,
and they already put this out.

07:59.334 --> 08:01.042
Huh.

08:01.125 --> 08:03.709
Hey, we said
a lot worse than this.
We didn't say anything bad.

08:03.792 --> 08:05.250
Langham: We said a lot worse
a month ago.

08:05.334 --> 08:07.542
Here it is, it just
happened while you were here.

08:07.626 --> 08:09.667
It was a very...
you guys were here

08:09.751 --> 08:13.125
at the making of
a lot of history today, guys.

08:13.209 --> 08:16.667
It's not a sure thing that
when you take a big decision

08:16.751 --> 08:19.792
and tell a CEO what to do,
they're going to listen.

08:19.876 --> 08:23.626
It's also not a sure thing
that your advice is
the right thing to do.

08:23.709 --> 08:25.083
You need chutzpah.

08:25.167 --> 08:27.584
You're taking on big-deal CEOs.

08:27.667 --> 08:29.918
You're taking on their lawyers.

08:30.000 --> 08:31.417
It's a very high-stakes game.

08:31.500 --> 08:34.167
You can make billions,
but you can also lose it.

08:34.250 --> 08:35.709
That is stressful.

08:35.792 --> 08:37.375
-Hey, Gail,
-Gail: Yes?

08:37.459 --> 08:38.751
Come in here
for a minute.

08:38.834 --> 08:41.626
Oh, I'm his consigliere.

08:41.709 --> 08:44.709
At night time, we join up
and then go home together.

08:44.792 --> 08:46.667
Bruce David Klein:
What do you think drives him?

08:46.751 --> 08:49.500
Oh! (sighs)

08:49.584 --> 08:51.417
It isn't money,
strangely enough.

08:51.500 --> 08:53.209
You would think
it would be money.

08:53.292 --> 08:57.000
I mean, it's nice
that he can do it,
but it's not money.

08:57.083 --> 08:59.334
He just becomes
obsessed on something

08:59.417 --> 09:01.000
and he just keeps
like a bulldog,

09:01.083 --> 09:03.751
he just keeps going and going
until he gets what he wants.

09:03.834 --> 09:06.125
So... that's what drives him.

09:06.209 --> 09:09.083
I told him it's winning,
I think, competitive,
just winning.

09:09.167 --> 09:12.751
Coming up with a new idea
to beat the competitors.

09:12.834 --> 09:14.042
You know, we're gonna
be able to be

09:14.125 --> 09:15.792
the biggest and the best.

09:15.876 --> 09:17.250
That gets me excited.

09:17.334 --> 09:20.876
♪ ♪

09:20.959 --> 09:24.959
<i>The money is just
sort of a goal.</i>

09:25.042 --> 09:29.042
<i>It's like, the explorers,
why do they keep doing it?</i>

09:29.125 --> 09:33.083
<i>They believed in going
for the gold, like Cortés
and these guys.</i>

09:35.167 --> 09:38.209
<i>But I think the actual
finding and doing</i>

09:38.292 --> 09:40.792
<i>is much more exciting
than having it.</i>

09:40.876 --> 09:43.417
♪ ♪

09:43.500 --> 09:44.959
<i>And I think
that's why you find</i>

09:45.042 --> 09:48.792
<i>a lot of rich people
get very neurotic.</i>

09:48.876 --> 09:51.792
<i>'Cause they're disappointed
when they have it.</i>

09:55.250 --> 09:57.459
<i>It's not what it's
drummed up to be.</i>

09:57.542 --> 10:00.250
♪ ♪

10:03.417 --> 10:05.959
reporter:
<i>He's been successful,</i>
<i>say Wall Streeters,</i>

10:06.042 --> 10:09.250
<i>because he's intimidating
and relentless.</i>

10:09.334 --> 10:12.250
<i>He was an only child
growing up during
the Depression</i>

10:12.334 --> 10:14.626
<i>in Far Rockaway, Queens,
New York.</i>

10:14.709 --> 10:18.709
<i>And even as a kid, his mother
said he was like Genghis Khan.</i>

10:18.792 --> 10:22.918
<i>He loves a good fight,
no doubt about it.</i>

10:23.000 --> 10:25.125
(percussive music playing)

10:31.125 --> 10:33.292
announcer:
<i>Tappan. Tappan.</i>

10:33.375 --> 10:36.417
<i>The name is Tappan.
Tappan... Tappan...</i>

10:36.500 --> 10:40.125
Mark Stevens:
<i>So in the late '70s,</i>
<i>Carl turned his attention</i>

10:40.209 --> 10:42.709
to a company called Tappan.

10:42.792 --> 10:44.500
<i>Tappan made ranges,</i>

10:44.584 --> 10:48.459
<i>and it was a good
brand-name range.</i>

10:48.542 --> 10:50.083
Bob Barker:
<i>Showcase number 2.</i>

10:50.167 --> 10:52.000
-announcer:<i> A new kitchen!</i>
-(audience gasps)

10:52.083 --> 10:53.876
<i>An electric range
from the famous Tappan.</i>

10:53.959 --> 10:57.292
<i>Quality appliances since 1881.</i>

10:57.375 --> 11:00.751
Tappan has its first loss
in nearly half a century.

11:04.292 --> 11:08.042
Because of the loss, and loss
of faith in the company,

11:08.125 --> 11:09.542
the stock plummeted

11:09.626 --> 11:11.751
to I think about
seven or eight bucks.

11:15.626 --> 11:17.417
So Carl does his calculations,

11:17.500 --> 11:20.125
assesses the valuation
of the company

11:20.209 --> 11:21.751
<i>between the stock price</i>

11:21.834 --> 11:23.667
<i>and the ultimate value
of the company.</i>

11:23.751 --> 11:28.542
<i>And there's a gap of about $15
that Carl feels is there.</i>

11:31.167 --> 11:33.834
Carl:<i> Well, we believed the</i>
<i>company was very undervalued.</i>

11:33.918 --> 11:36.375
And Tappan fit
the program for me

11:36.459 --> 11:38.417
where I was embarking
on activism,

11:38.500 --> 11:42.417
where I thought it was
a great company, a great name,

11:42.500 --> 11:44.709
that could be
a takeover candidate

11:44.792 --> 11:47.584
being blocked by,
you know, the CEO

11:47.667 --> 11:48.876
<i>and a board.</i>

11:48.959 --> 11:51.834
<i>The CEO was
a very strong personality,</i>

11:51.918 --> 11:55.959
<i>but I don't think he knew
much about the business.</i>

11:56.042 --> 11:59.125
<i>And Dick Tappan was
the founder's grandson.</i>

11:59.209 --> 12:02.459
<i>I think he was intimidated
by this guy Blasius.</i>

12:02.542 --> 12:06.584
<i>And I thought there was
a chance here to break through.</i>

12:06.667 --> 12:08.834
So we went and bought
a lot of stock in it.

12:10.500 --> 12:14.584
And, uh, we would then
make a little noise.

12:16.959 --> 12:19.167
(intense digital music playing)

12:24.334 --> 12:27.751
Carl:<i> "I'm writing this letter</i>
<i>to ask you to elect me</i>

12:27.834 --> 12:29.584
<i>to the board of directors."</i>

12:29.667 --> 12:33.167
♪ ♪

12:33.250 --> 12:34.709
<i>"During the past five years,</i>

12:34.792 --> 12:37.125
<i>"Tappan, under its
current management,</i>

12:37.209 --> 12:39.709
<i>has lost $3.3 million."</i>

12:47.500 --> 12:49.500
The company is owned
by the shareholders

12:49.584 --> 12:51.834
and these managements felt like,

12:51.918 --> 12:53.751
"We don't wanna deal
with these shareholders."

12:53.834 --> 12:56.209
"They thought they'd get
under our skin? No."

12:58.542 --> 13:01.667
We ran a proxy fight
and they fought us like hell.

13:01.751 --> 13:04.000
♪ ♪

13:15.375 --> 13:18.834
It's just amazing.
Carl got a seat on the board.

13:20.667 --> 13:22.459
<i>I think we were the wave.</i>

13:22.542 --> 13:25.459
There was not anybody really
doing what we were doing.

13:25.542 --> 13:29.292
(relaxing music playing)

13:32.667 --> 13:35.292
Stevens:
<i>When Carl goes to Ohio</i>

13:35.375 --> 13:37.125
<i>to visit with
Tappan management,</i>

13:37.209 --> 13:40.125
<i>it's an orderly life there,</i>

13:40.209 --> 13:43.000
and everything is in
the right place.

13:45.500 --> 13:47.083
The CEO called me up.

13:47.167 --> 13:49.500
He said, "I wanna have dinner
with you before the meeting."

13:49.584 --> 13:53.167
<i>So I thought he'd want to have
a sort of nice chat with me.</i>

13:53.250 --> 13:55.417
And he looked at me and he was
sort of fierce-looking.

13:55.500 --> 13:59.083
He said, "Look,
at my board meeting,
you're an interloper.

13:59.167 --> 14:02.375
"I don't want you to say
anything at the meetings.

14:02.459 --> 14:06.083
I don't want you to disturb
the rest of the board
and we can get along better."

14:06.167 --> 14:08.000
And I was just
beginning this stuff.

14:08.083 --> 14:10.876
Today, I would have
told him to go to hell.

14:10.959 --> 14:13.083
Alfred Kingsley:
<i>The next day, Carl came</i>

14:13.167 --> 14:14.751
and we went into the meeting,

14:14.834 --> 14:18.083
which was pretty contentious.

14:18.167 --> 14:21.500
Carl:<i> And the CEO decided</i>
<i>to buy another company.</i>

14:21.584 --> 14:23.542
<i>And he brought it
to the board.</i>

14:23.626 --> 14:26.959
He was gonna make
the company less valuable

14:27.042 --> 14:29.542
in a strange way
but him more powerful.

14:29.626 --> 14:34.167
And the CEO is showing
everybody with his books
and his investment bankers

14:34.250 --> 14:36.459
why this was
a great acquisition.

14:36.542 --> 14:39.292
<i>The CEO, he said, "Look, I've
done a lot of work on this.</i>

14:39.375 --> 14:43.209
<i>I just want a vote
that agrees with me."</i>

14:43.292 --> 14:47.959
And this one guy on the board
who never really spoke either

14:48.042 --> 14:50.792
but who owned a lot of stock,
he said, "Just a minute."

14:50.876 --> 14:52.500
<i>He says, "I'm looking at this.</i>

14:52.584 --> 14:55.250
<i>I just don't understand
why we're buying it
with these numbers."</i>

14:55.334 --> 14:58.918
The CEO, he says, "Are you
questioning my judgment?"

14:59.000 --> 15:00.209
He's glaring at the guy.

15:00.292 --> 15:03.709
<i>He says, "Sit down and vote
with all of us."</i>

15:03.792 --> 15:06.125
<i>He really was an imperious guy.</i>

15:06.209 --> 15:09.000
And I'm watching
to see what to do.

15:09.083 --> 15:12.459
And, you know, at that time,
I didn't think anybody
would support me

15:12.542 --> 15:15.417
if I said anything,
but I said, "The hell
with this guy Blasius."

15:15.500 --> 15:18.250
By that time, I didn't give
a damn if he liked me,
didn't like me.

15:18.334 --> 15:20.417
(intense digital music playing)

15:20.500 --> 15:23.000
<i>So I go, "Screw this guy."</i>

15:23.083 --> 15:26.000
Stevens:
<i>In this Tappan time,</i>
<i>one could think</i>

15:26.083 --> 15:27.667
that Carl didn't have the...

15:27.751 --> 15:30.042
kahunas that he would have
later in big deals.

15:30.125 --> 15:31.334
He had more then.

15:31.417 --> 15:33.417
He had to do it with nothing.

15:33.500 --> 15:35.417
He didn't have
billions in the bank.

15:35.500 --> 15:38.834
Carl:<i> I said,</i>
<i>"You know something, guys,</i>
<i>I'll tell you what I think."</i>

15:38.918 --> 15:42.125
<i>"This is probably
one of the worst deals</i>

15:42.209 --> 15:44.500
"in, I'll say,
economic history.

15:44.584 --> 15:48.876
"It's insane.
We're buying this company
at ten times what it's worth,

15:48.959 --> 15:52.375
only," I say,
"to save Don Blasius' job.

15:52.459 --> 15:54.918
<i>That's why we're doing it."
I really let him have it.</i>

15:55.000 --> 15:57.250
And the guy was going nuts.
He was turning red in the face.

15:57.334 --> 16:00.500
He says, "What are you saying?
Are you questioning my ability?"
I said, "Yes, I am.

16:00.584 --> 16:04.250
I don't think you're a good
CEO, you're just gonna
kill this company."

16:04.334 --> 16:06.876
All of the sudden, Carl,
he's not talking,

16:06.959 --> 16:09.459
he's yelling, he's demanding.

16:09.542 --> 16:14.209
"I, for one, will do everything
I can to stop this deal,

16:14.292 --> 16:16.042
"and now I'm saying it
to this board,

16:16.125 --> 16:17.584
so now let's have the vote."

16:17.667 --> 16:21.542
And Blasius is looking at me,
red in the face and all.

16:21.626 --> 16:24.834
And he says, "We'll put off
the vote till the next meeting."

16:24.918 --> 16:28.500
And then he just glowered at me,
and I just looked at him,

16:28.584 --> 16:31.417
and that was it.

16:31.500 --> 16:33.292
People are scratching
their heads saying, how the--

16:33.375 --> 16:36.667
"What the hell just happened?
Who is this guy?"

16:36.751 --> 16:40.876
<i>"How did he foil the plans of
the CEO of a public company?"</i>

16:42.292 --> 16:44.751
<i>And then, only seven or eight
months later,</i>

16:44.834 --> 16:47.500
Electrolux agreed to buy Tappan

16:47.584 --> 16:49.834
for a little over
$18 a share...

16:49.918 --> 16:52.125
♪ ♪

16:52.209 --> 16:54.000
<i>...proving in absolute terms,</i>

16:54.083 --> 16:56.209
Carl was right from
the beginning.

16:56.292 --> 17:00.918
<i>Tappan was worth
a lot more than the $7
the stock was trading at</i>

17:01.000 --> 17:02.876
<i>before Carl got involved.</i>

17:02.959 --> 17:04.959
And all the shareholders
got richer.

17:07.375 --> 17:08.876
Carl:<i> At the end,</i>

17:08.959 --> 17:10.834
<i>Dick Tappan comes over to me</i>

17:10.918 --> 17:13.667
and he says, "Carl, Carl,
I wanna ask you a question.

17:13.751 --> 17:16.083
Would you manage my money?"

17:16.167 --> 17:18.542
And he wanted me
to manage money for him.

17:18.626 --> 17:19.959
And I did for a little bit.

17:20.042 --> 17:23.918
(contemplative piano music
playing)

17:24.000 --> 17:27.459
This is Carl, Carl Icahn on.

17:27.542 --> 17:29.417
If I could interrupt
for a minute.

17:29.500 --> 17:31.626
The CEO was just nefarious.

17:31.709 --> 17:35.375
He, his job in his mind was
to make himself a lot of money

17:35.459 --> 17:37.500
at the expense of shareholders,
he didn't care.

17:37.584 --> 17:40.792
And at the expense of
the company enriched himself.

17:40.876 --> 17:44.209
The idea that
some management teams

17:44.292 --> 17:46.209
were kind of not being
very smart

17:46.292 --> 17:49.709
and taking advantage of
their position as managers

17:49.792 --> 17:51.584
to the detriment
of the shareholders,

17:51.667 --> 17:54.042
you know, he got that
in his head early on,

17:54.125 --> 17:56.334
when the rest of the world
wasn't quite sure, you know,

17:56.417 --> 17:58.751
was this greenmail,
what, what was this?

17:58.834 --> 18:01.834
This is one of-- the most
reprehensible thing

18:01.918 --> 18:03.459
I think I've ever seen...

18:03.542 --> 18:06.584
But to some degree
he's been vindicated that,

18:06.667 --> 18:09.459
yes, management often needs
to be shaken up.

18:09.542 --> 18:12.167
He's helped stockholders
an awful lot,

18:12.250 --> 18:15.834
including plumbers and teachers
whose pension funds

18:15.918 --> 18:17.334
fund their retirement.

18:17.417 --> 18:21.042
So this is not just hoity-toity
big-time investors.

18:21.125 --> 18:23.209
The downside of that
is to say, yeah, but what about

18:23.292 --> 18:26.667
all the people
who lost jobs because of what
Carl did at all these companies?

18:26.751 --> 18:29.250
(somber digital music playing)

18:33.334 --> 18:37.626
Carl and guys like him, I think
the core criticism would be that

18:37.709 --> 18:39.626
they're not out to make
these companies better,

18:39.709 --> 18:41.334
they're out to make
a lot of money.

18:43.542 --> 18:46.626
Part of my values
is to make money and I
can't change my values.

18:46.709 --> 18:48.125
A great painter loves to paint.

18:48.209 --> 18:50.292
What do you do, criticize him
because he likes to paint?

18:50.375 --> 18:54.209
But what makes me fulfilled
about it is

18:54.292 --> 18:58.417
that I also believe I'm making
money by doing the right thing.

18:58.500 --> 19:01.292
Sorkin:<i> We've been having</i>
<i>a debate, it's an open debate,</i>

19:01.375 --> 19:03.584
'cause I've done it
in the columns,

19:03.667 --> 19:07.626
about his role as a vulture

19:07.709 --> 19:10.667
or a shareholder advocate,
and which is it?

19:10.751 --> 19:14.083
<i>And on certain days,
I've come out on the side</i>

19:14.167 --> 19:17.500
of shareholder advocate,
and he, you know, loves it.

19:17.584 --> 19:20.459
And on certain days,
I have called him a vulture,

19:20.542 --> 19:22.083
and he'll call up screaming.

19:23.584 --> 19:26.959
What I like about Carl
is he's game for the debate,

19:27.042 --> 19:28.792
he wants that debate.

19:28.876 --> 19:31.250
Carl:<i> Companies are</i>
<i>the backbone of our society,</i>

19:31.334 --> 19:34.375
and many are terribly managed
and there's no accountability.

19:34.459 --> 19:36.667
When you can change that,

19:36.751 --> 19:38.083
you will have
some collateral damage,

19:38.167 --> 19:40.751
there's no question,
it's creative destruction.

19:40.834 --> 19:43.083
But we bring in the innovation,

19:43.167 --> 19:45.959
so we have companies
that are more productive,

19:46.042 --> 19:48.500
create more jobs,
in a macro picture.

19:48.584 --> 19:49.876
At the end of the day,

19:49.959 --> 19:52.417
Carl wants to make as much
money as possible,

19:52.500 --> 19:56.334
despite what he may come out
and say publicly

19:56.417 --> 19:58.167
or write in one of his letters.

19:58.250 --> 20:00.125
I mean, that's
the criticism you hear.

20:00.209 --> 20:02.709
Carl:<i> So everybody says,</i>
<i>"Well, that's great,</i>

20:02.792 --> 20:04.792
<i>Carl Icahn made money
for himself."</i>

20:04.876 --> 20:08.042
But the real proof of
the pudding is in the eating.

20:08.125 --> 20:11.959
If you had invested
in Icahn Enterprises in 2000,

20:12.042 --> 20:14.792
when we really started
getting into the activism,

20:14.876 --> 20:17.459
the value of your investment
has increased

20:17.542 --> 20:19.626
1,931%.

20:19.709 --> 20:23.042
During that same period,
your investment in the S&P

20:23.125 --> 20:26.709
went up only 324%.

20:28.709 --> 20:30.626
<i>We have made for shareholders,</i>

20:30.709 --> 20:32.209
<i>forgetting us,</i>

20:32.292 --> 20:33.709
<i>literally a trillion dollars</i>

20:33.792 --> 20:35.417
<i>for all investors.</i>

20:37.167 --> 20:39.584
I think I proved it
by making all this money.

20:39.667 --> 20:41.167
This system should be changed

20:41.250 --> 20:43.292
and that we should have true
corporate democracy

20:43.375 --> 20:44.709
and accountability.

20:48.167 --> 20:51.292
Frankly, I made this money
because the system is so bad,

20:51.375 --> 20:52.834
not 'cause I'm a genius.

20:52.918 --> 20:54.500
(marching band plays)

20:54.584 --> 20:56.209
announcer:
<i>This is New York.</i>

20:56.292 --> 20:57.417
<i>A miracle city.</i>

20:57.500 --> 20:58.751
<i>A monument to our nation's</i>

20:58.834 --> 20:59.834
<i>restless energy.</i>

20:59.918 --> 21:01.667
<i>Across the river from Manhattan</i>

21:01.751 --> 21:03.834
<i>lies the borough of Queens.</i>

21:03.918 --> 21:06.667
(jazz band playing)

21:06.751 --> 21:09.709
Carl:<i> I grew up</i>
<i>in the streets of Queens.</i>

21:11.083 --> 21:12.500
<i>It was sort of divided.</i>

21:12.584 --> 21:14.792
<i>In public school, you had
some of these middle-class,</i>

21:14.876 --> 21:16.125
<i>mostly Jewish kids.</i>

21:16.209 --> 21:18.125
<i>From the other side
of the tracks,</i>

21:18.209 --> 21:19.667
<i>a lot of
the reform school kids,</i>

21:19.751 --> 21:21.459
<i>and those were the kids
I liked, really.</i>

21:21.542 --> 21:24.709
<i>Used to play basketball
with the Gotti brothers.</i>

21:24.792 --> 21:28.292
But the more my mother said,
"Don't do it," the more
I wanted to do it.

21:28.375 --> 21:32.125
Stevens:<i> Bella Icahn</i>
<i>was the school teacher</i>

21:32.209 --> 21:35.083
who was always teaching school.

21:35.959 --> 21:38.375
<i>Carl's father was a cantor,</i>

21:38.459 --> 21:41.792
<i>the guy who sings
in a synagogue,</i>

21:41.876 --> 21:43.626
<i>who pressed Carl</i>

21:43.709 --> 21:46.500
on philosophers and philosophies
and was unrelenting,

21:46.584 --> 21:48.876
and his mother, who was
unrelenting another way.

21:48.959 --> 21:50.667
She wanted him to go
to medical school,

21:50.751 --> 21:52.542
but they were both
very intense people.

21:52.626 --> 21:54.375
He had a tough childhood.

21:54.459 --> 21:57.584
I mean, you know, his parents
would brag about him in public

21:57.667 --> 21:59.500
but kind of berate him,
privately.

21:59.584 --> 22:01.709
(contemplative music playing)

22:08.584 --> 22:12.459
I was never really happy
in that whole environment.

22:12.542 --> 22:14.167
So I really wanted
to get out of there.

22:14.250 --> 22:16.709
I was real smart in school,
and I had good marks.

22:16.792 --> 22:20.083
<i>I took the college boards,</i>

22:20.167 --> 22:23.959
<i>and I think I did the best
in Queens or something on 'em.</i>

22:24.042 --> 22:26.417
And my father did say to me,

22:26.500 --> 22:29.209
"If you get into Yale,
Harvard or Princeton,

22:29.292 --> 22:30.876
we'll pay the tuition."

22:30.959 --> 22:33.083
<i>'Cause they figured
nobody ever got in</i>

22:33.167 --> 22:34.584
<i>from Far Rockaway
High School.</i>

22:34.667 --> 22:37.459
<i>And so I got into all of 'em.</i>

22:37.542 --> 22:40.751
And everybody
was really surprised,
including my parents.

22:40.834 --> 22:43.709
<i>I wanted Princeton.</i>

22:43.792 --> 22:46.042
But then when it came
to thinking about paying
the tuition,

22:46.125 --> 22:50.292
it was only $750 in those days,
and the room and board was $750.

22:50.375 --> 22:53.083
<i>My father said, "Son, we're
not gonna go back on our word.</i>

22:53.167 --> 22:54.542
<i>We're gonna pay your tuition."</i>

22:54.626 --> 22:56.209
<i>I said,
"Thanks, Dad, that's great.</i>

22:56.292 --> 22:57.751
<i>I appreciate it greatly."</i>

22:57.834 --> 22:58.959
And then it hit me, I said,

22:59.042 --> 23:00.667
"What about
room and board, Dad?"

23:00.751 --> 23:03.125
<i>And then he said,
"You're a smart kid.</i>

23:03.209 --> 23:05.667
<i>You gotta worry about
the room and board yourself."</i>

23:05.751 --> 23:08.667
(doo-wop music playing)

23:12.834 --> 23:16.959
<i>So, somehow
I wheedled myself a job</i>

23:17.042 --> 23:18.292
<i>on Atlantic Beach,</i>

23:18.375 --> 23:21.250
<i>the sort of, in quotes,
"wealthy people" came.</i>

23:21.334 --> 23:24.042
<i>So I'm a cabana boy,
figure I'll work for tips.</i>

23:24.125 --> 23:27.250
<i>And you could make close
to $100 a week.</i>

23:27.334 --> 23:30.375
And these salesmen,
for the most part from Brooklyn,

23:30.459 --> 23:33.000
<i>were playing poker.</i>

23:33.083 --> 23:35.292
<i>And once they said,
"Kid, how much you make?"</i>

23:35.375 --> 23:37.250
<i>I said, "Hey,
I made a hundred bucks."</i>

23:37.334 --> 23:39.542
"Okay, you got a hundred bucks,
you wanna lose it,

23:39.626 --> 23:42.459
come here, do a game, we'll
show you what life's about."

23:42.542 --> 23:45.667
<i>So I said, "Yeah,
I think I could play."</i>

23:45.751 --> 23:48.584
And they wiped me out
in about a half an hour.

23:48.667 --> 23:49.959
I lost the $100.

23:50.042 --> 23:52.709
I said, "Hey, I'm smarter
than these guys."

23:52.792 --> 23:56.500
<i>So during the week, I went out,
I got three books on poker.</i>

23:56.584 --> 23:58.334
<i>And it's really
a mathematical game.</i>

23:58.417 --> 24:00.918
<i>It's luck, too, but
these guys were not that good.</i>

24:01.000 --> 24:02.959
<i>To begin with,
they were drinking vodka,</i>

24:03.042 --> 24:04.792
<i>and they were just having fun.</i>

24:04.876 --> 24:06.709
<i>The next week,</i>

24:06.792 --> 24:09.626
I went in and I said,
"I'll play it again."

24:09.709 --> 24:13.709
<i>They said, "Okay, kid,
you haven't learned
your lesson yet."</i>

24:13.792 --> 24:15.709
<i>And then I killed 'em.</i>

24:15.792 --> 24:17.417
<i>I got inordinately lucky.</i>

24:17.500 --> 24:21.542
<i>And literally that weekend,
I won $800.</i>

24:22.417 --> 24:25.542
♪ ♪

24:25.626 --> 24:27.918
And that's how I paid
my room and board

24:28.000 --> 24:29.500
throughout Princeton.

24:29.584 --> 24:31.959
(playful digital music playing)

24:39.959 --> 24:42.792
Gail:<i> I can tell you</i>
<i>the first moment</i>
<i>I fell in love with Carl,</i>

24:42.876 --> 24:45.667
<i>and that was when I
started working for him</i>

24:45.751 --> 24:48.500
<i>and heard him on the phone
speaking to his uncle,</i>

24:48.584 --> 24:50.751
<i>who had offended him
in some way.</i>

24:50.834 --> 24:54.792
<i>And he was so frank
in that exchange.</i>

24:54.876 --> 24:57.375
<i>Coming from
an Irish background</i>

24:57.459 --> 25:00.125
<i>where everything
is sort of hidden,</i>

25:00.209 --> 25:03.209
I was not accustomed to

25:03.292 --> 25:06.834
that kind of depth of feeling
and that honesty of feeling,

25:06.918 --> 25:10.334
and I think that was
the first moment that I thought,

25:10.417 --> 25:14.083
"This guy has a little bit
more substance than
I thought he did," so...

25:15.125 --> 25:18.125
Oh, God, this elbow's
killing me.

25:18.209 --> 25:20.792
Well, you played pretty well
with the elbow killing you.

25:20.876 --> 25:22.584
Well, imagine the trouble
you're going to be in.

25:22.667 --> 25:24.500
Carl: Yeah, imagine if you
didn't have a bad elbow.

25:24.584 --> 25:27.709
You know, you hit those goddamn
little poopy shots at me,

25:27.792 --> 25:30.709
which, you know,
it throws me off my game.

25:30.792 --> 25:33.876
You know, that's, you know,
in some cases that's by design.

25:33.959 --> 25:35.876
I know you don't think that,
but it's by design.

25:35.959 --> 25:37.918
-Sometimes I just...
-Baloney, it's by design.

25:38.000 --> 25:41.167
There are times
I play with you when
I deliberately hit it soft.

25:41.250 --> 25:43.792
You're not good enough
to deliberately hit it soft.

25:43.876 --> 25:45.959
You don't have a slice.
You don't, yeah.

25:46.042 --> 25:47.959
I don't have to have a slice.

25:48.042 --> 25:50.167
Yeah, I mean, you played well,
you played well.

25:50.250 --> 25:53.751
You actually, you actually
really did okay yesterday,

25:53.834 --> 25:57.000
got to admit,
with a bad elbow.

25:57.083 --> 25:59.918
Gail:<i> We started</i>
<i>living together in '92,</i>

26:00.000 --> 26:01.876
<i>and didn't get married
until '99.</i>

26:01.959 --> 26:03.459
This is another horror story

26:03.542 --> 26:05.834
from a client from TWA.

26:05.918 --> 26:07.667
Gail:<i> But I have</i>
<i>known him since '78.</i>

26:07.751 --> 26:09.584
<i>I started working
for him in '78.</i>

26:09.667 --> 26:12.918
<i>The first time I met Carl,
this employment agency said,</i>

26:13.000 --> 26:15.125
<i>"Can you please come in?"
and she said,</i>

26:15.209 --> 26:19.459
"I have this guy,
I've had a hard time
keeping people with him."

26:19.542 --> 26:20.876
-That's not true.
-Gail: Oh!

26:20.959 --> 26:22.500
I've had people
with me 20 years.

26:22.584 --> 26:24.375
I'm not gonna lie on camera,
so you can just go ahead

26:24.459 --> 26:26.292
-and say what you wanna say.
-Eh...

26:26.375 --> 26:30.626
But anyways, the pile of stuff
on his desk was incredible.

26:30.709 --> 26:33.834
So he says, "Do you think
you could help me with this?"

26:33.918 --> 26:38.167
This chaos, and in the first
two weeks, I was ready to quit.

26:38.250 --> 26:39.250
<i>But he was fun.</i>

26:39.334 --> 26:41.125
<i>He was just very fun.</i>

26:41.209 --> 26:43.500
And so, you know,
it started there.

26:43.584 --> 26:44.876
And it was, it was good.

26:44.959 --> 26:48.417
Tony Bennett:
<i>♪ I'm steppin' out</i>
<i>with my baby ♪</i>

26:48.500 --> 26:50.918
<i>♪ Can't go wrong
'cause I'm in right ♪</i>

26:51.000 --> 26:54.167
<i>♪ It's for sure,
not for maybe ♪</i>

26:54.250 --> 26:56.834
<i>♪ That I'm all
dressed up tonight ♪</i>

26:56.918 --> 26:59.375
<i>-♪ Steppin' out with my honey ♪</i>
-You're gettin' too good...

26:59.459 --> 27:02.334
<i>♪ Can't be bad,
feels so good ♪</i>

27:02.417 --> 27:05.167
<i>♪ Never felt quite so sunny ♪</i>

27:05.250 --> 27:08.042
<i>♪ And I keep on
knockin' wood... ♪</i>

27:08.125 --> 27:11.876
I think what keeps it going
is respect for each other.

27:11.959 --> 27:13.626
Um, and we laugh a lot.

27:13.709 --> 27:17.125
I mean, there's a lot of banter,
you know, sarcasm,
back and forth.

27:17.209 --> 27:20.042
-Doesn't matter what you think.
-Gail: It doesn't matter
what<i> you</i> think.

27:20.125 --> 27:22.167
-Who cares what you think?
-Who cares what<i> you</i> think?

27:22.250 --> 27:24.876
We can banter with each other,

27:24.959 --> 27:30.042
but she's one of the few people
whose opinion I really value.

27:30.125 --> 27:33.042
Some nights I fall asleep
in the bath.

27:33.125 --> 27:34.667
And Gail turns a movie on

27:34.751 --> 27:37.125
and doesn't bother
to tell me she leaves.

27:37.209 --> 27:39.709
And I wake up and say,
"Holy, where am I?"

27:39.792 --> 27:43.709
I say, "Gail, maybe you could
have waked me up, check in.

27:43.792 --> 27:46.000
I could have been dead
