And, you see, this is the way
he was in the restaurant,

53:47.876 --> 53:49.334
when we talked about it.

53:49.417 --> 53:51.125
You see the shoes.

53:51.209 --> 53:53.292
And he was a real character.

53:53.375 --> 53:55.584
And he writes, "Friend Carl,

53:55.667 --> 53:56.751
shit happens."

53:56.834 --> 53:59.125
"Joe Jamail."

53:59.209 --> 54:01.125
So I keep this around.

54:04.292 --> 54:07.083
(tranquil music playing)

54:07.167 --> 54:09.250
<i>When I started out,</i>

54:09.334 --> 54:12.709
<i>I learned the hard way,</i>

54:12.792 --> 54:17.500
<i>playing the market,
it's a competitive area,
it's gambling.</i>

54:17.584 --> 54:21.375
<i>Too many variables, too many
people competing with you.</i>

54:21.459 --> 54:26.292
<i>You can't believe that
the gambling will carry you.</i>

54:26.375 --> 54:32.709
♪ ♪

54:32.792 --> 54:36.417
<i>So, you look for something
I call a "no-brainer."</i>

54:36.500 --> 54:39.042
<i>Very little risk,
but a lot of reward.</i>

54:39.125 --> 54:41.876
<i>After a while, it becomes
somewhat instinctive,</i>

54:41.959 --> 54:46.542
<i>that you see something
that's not really apparent
to everyone.</i>

54:46.626 --> 54:48.709
♪ ♪

54:57.167 --> 54:59.876
<i>But there's tough times
when you're not gonna enjoy it.</i>

54:59.959 --> 55:02.375
<i>You know, you're gonna lose
and you gotta be
willing to say,</i>

55:02.459 --> 55:03.876
<i>"Hey, if I lose, so what?"</i>

55:03.959 --> 55:07.292
<i>It's like that great
Rudyard Kipling poem.</i>

55:07.375 --> 55:10.792
<i>"If you can meet
with Triumph and Disaster</i>

55:10.876 --> 55:15.209
<i>and treat those two impostors
just the same..."</i>

55:15.292 --> 55:16.918
<i>That's important.</i>

55:17.000 --> 55:19.250
♪ ♪

55:26.042 --> 55:30.167
<i>But you have to have
a passion for it.</i>

55:30.250 --> 55:33.000
<i>You get a great feeling
when you find a company,</i>

55:33.083 --> 55:35.292
<i>when you find something
you can do.</i>

55:35.375 --> 55:36.918
<i>You get excited by it.</i>

55:37.042 --> 55:40.083
<i>And by instinct now,
something goes "click,"</i>

55:40.167 --> 55:42.083
<i>and you know it's good.</i>

55:42.167 --> 55:44.250
<i>It all sums up
in that movie "The Hustler,"</i>

55:44.334 --> 55:48.417
<i>where, when he shoots
the ball, he says...</i>

55:48.500 --> 55:50.334
<i>You know,
I got a hunch, fat man.</i>

55:50.417 --> 55:52.709
<i>I got a hunch
it's me from here on in.</i>

55:53.918 --> 55:55.542
<i>One ball, corner pocket.</i>

55:57.042 --> 55:58.959
<i>I mean,
that ever happen to you,</i>

55:59.042 --> 56:02.125
<i>where all of a sudden,
you feel like you can't miss?</i>

56:05.584 --> 56:09.083
When I hear the click,
I know I won.

56:12.375 --> 56:14.542
(rhythmic percussion
music playing)

56:20.459 --> 56:23.709
<i>♪ Leading the way ♪</i>

56:23.792 --> 56:26.375
announcer:
<i>TWA presents the difference</i>

56:26.459 --> 56:28.584
<i>between getting you
where you're going</i>

56:28.667 --> 56:30.709
<i>and leading the way.</i>

56:30.792 --> 56:32.459
(upbeat music playing)

56:32.542 --> 56:33.792
<i>What's that?</i>

56:33.876 --> 56:35.334
-(reporters laughing)
<i>-What was that?</i>

56:35.417 --> 56:38.292
man:<i> Waiting for</i>
<i>the equipment to warm up.</i>

56:38.375 --> 56:41.334
<i>I see you have problems
with equipment as we do.</i>

56:41.417 --> 56:43.250
<i>Uh...</i>

56:43.334 --> 56:45.125
<i>I thank you all for coming.</i>

56:45.209 --> 56:47.209
<i>I'd just like to say that, uh,</i>

56:47.292 --> 56:50.083
<i>we're doing quite well
with our scheduling.</i>

56:50.167 --> 56:53.709
<i>TWA, I can tell you now
for sure, is here to stay.</i>

56:53.792 --> 56:58.209
(somber music playing)

57:07.125 --> 57:10.834
Burrough:
<i>This was an awful time</i>
<i>in the airline business.</i>

57:10.918 --> 57:13.250
And a lot of these companies
were under fire,

57:13.334 --> 57:15.459
were the focus
of corporate raiders.

57:15.542 --> 57:17.417
And when this fella,
Frank Lorenzo,

57:17.500 --> 57:19.584
goes after TWA...

57:21.417 --> 57:24.292
he was deeply, deeply
unpopular in the business.

57:24.375 --> 57:27.459
<i>Show me a business person
that doesn't like a monopoly</i>

57:27.542 --> 57:29.125
<i>and I'll show you a big liar.</i>

57:29.209 --> 57:30.959
-(audience laughing)
<i>-Okay?</i>

57:31.042 --> 57:34.876
reporter:<i> Lorenzo was known</i>
<i>for being tough on unions.</i>

57:34.959 --> 57:36.834
Burrough:
<i>So, at TWA,</i>

57:36.918 --> 57:39.375
the unions actually
went to Carl.

57:41.292 --> 57:43.042
Carl:
<i>So they all met with me.</i>

57:43.125 --> 57:44.542
They really wanted me to come in

57:44.626 --> 57:47.292
because they needed somebody
to fight off Lorenzo.

57:47.375 --> 57:49.959
announcer:
<i>Today's TWA is the new spirit</i>

57:50.042 --> 57:52.083
<i>and vitality of our people.</i>

57:52.167 --> 57:55.834
So they said, "We'll give you
huge concessions if you do it."

57:55.918 --> 57:58.125
So I looked at the numbers
and said, "Yeah,

57:58.209 --> 58:00.292
"if you guys give
these concessions,

58:00.375 --> 58:02.751
you could just save
a lot of capital here."

58:02.834 --> 58:04.876
(music box playing)

58:08.083 --> 58:10.876
The staff gave me
this toy plane

58:10.959 --> 58:12.876
to commemorate the TWA deal.

58:12.959 --> 58:15.751
(music box playing)

58:17.918 --> 58:23.417
Carl Icahn takes control
and is now running TWA.

58:23.500 --> 58:26.083
Carl Icahn,
the controversial financier

58:26.167 --> 58:28.751
known for his attacks
on corporate management.

58:28.834 --> 58:31.375
Now they will be watching
to see how he himself

58:31.459 --> 58:33.626
handles the management
of a major corporation.

58:33.709 --> 58:35.417
♪ ♪

58:35.500 --> 58:37.709
Wapner:<i> Carl had never</i>
<i>run anything before.</i>

58:37.792 --> 58:40.250
<i>Certainly nothing
like an airline.</i>

58:40.334 --> 58:42.125
You're dealing with the economy,

58:42.209 --> 58:43.751
you're dealing with unions,

58:43.834 --> 58:47.209
and that was his biggest fight
right off the bat.

58:47.292 --> 58:49.709
<i>We want a TWA that can exist
and it will exist</i>

58:49.792 --> 58:52.459
<i>because all the employees
have come behind us.</i>

58:52.542 --> 58:54.167
<i>The employees have given.</i>

58:54.250 --> 58:56.834
When it came time
to give the concessions,

58:56.918 --> 59:01.542
the pilots lived up
to their bargain
and so did the machinists,

59:01.626 --> 59:03.375
and then the flight attendants,
Vicki Frankovich,

59:03.459 --> 59:05.834
comes in and says,
"We can't do it."

59:08.375 --> 59:12.667
Carl Icahn came in and demanded
changes in everything.

59:12.751 --> 59:14.626
She said,
"You got enough, it's too bad."

59:14.709 --> 59:17.417
I said, "Bullshit. You made
a deal, you got to stick to it."

59:21.667 --> 59:24.876
striker:
Carl Icahn not fair
to flight attendants!

59:24.959 --> 59:28.083
Fifteen days into the strike
by TWA flight attendants,

59:28.167 --> 59:32.000
<i>there is no sign of
conciliation by either side.</i>

59:32.083 --> 59:35.209
At issue, company-proposed
wage rollbacks.

59:35.292 --> 59:38.667
<i>TWA employees confronting
a bottom-line businessman.</i>

59:38.751 --> 59:40.709
<i>The work rules
we must have to survive.</i>

59:40.792 --> 59:42.292
We are not asking
for very much.

59:42.375 --> 59:44.751
The changes he's asking
are drastic.

59:44.834 --> 59:46.292
Carl:<i> This company</i>
<i>would have been bankrupt</i>

59:46.375 --> 59:48.292
<i>if I hadn't come along
and saved the damn thing.</i>

59:48.375 --> 59:50.584
Carl Icahn
is a corporate raider.

59:50.667 --> 59:52.250
<i>♪ TWA ♪</i>

59:52.334 --> 59:55.000
You know, literally they'd say,
"We got you by the balls,

59:55.083 --> 59:58.292
the great Mr. Icahn,
because you need us to fly."

59:58.375 --> 1:00:01.209
♪ ♪

1:00:01.292 --> 1:00:03.334
So, what I thought of is this,
I said, "Wait a minute,

1:00:03.417 --> 1:00:05.834
why can't we just bring in
new flight attendants?"

1:00:05.918 --> 1:00:08.209
"Oh, because they gotta
be licensed."

1:00:08.292 --> 1:00:10.626
-(alert chimes)
-(air hisses)

1:00:10.709 --> 1:00:13.834
I said, "Set up a school
for flight attendants."

1:00:13.918 --> 1:00:15.459
"Eh, I don't know.

1:00:15.542 --> 1:00:17.751
We can't do that."
I said, "Well, why not?"

1:00:17.834 --> 1:00:19.042
"Nobody ever did that."

1:00:19.125 --> 1:00:20.918
I said, "Set up
the goddamn school,"

1:00:21.000 --> 1:00:23.292
and from all over the country,
I couldn't believe it,

1:00:23.375 --> 1:00:25.334
all these people want
to be flight attendants.

1:00:25.417 --> 1:00:28.083
And then Frankovich
now goes crazy.

1:00:28.167 --> 1:00:31.083
She sees all this happening.

1:00:31.167 --> 1:00:34.709
striker: The flight attendants
are out here today because
they want to show Carl Icahn

1:00:34.792 --> 1:00:37.500
that we are still united
and we're still determined
to win this battle.

1:00:37.584 --> 1:00:41.542
We're holding together better
than any other union I know
that has struck in the past.

1:00:41.626 --> 1:00:44.876
Some woman down the road
calls me up, panicked.

1:00:44.959 --> 1:00:47.167
"There are a thousand people
walking up the road,

1:00:47.250 --> 1:00:48.459
chanting and screaming."

1:00:48.542 --> 1:00:50.167
"What's going on, Carl?"
you know.

1:00:50.250 --> 1:00:53.167
She says,
"I'm calling the police.
I'm calling the police."

1:00:53.250 --> 1:00:54.751
(siren wails)

1:00:54.834 --> 1:00:57.918
(intense music playing)

1:00:58.000 --> 1:01:00.250
(strikers chanting)

1:01:00.334 --> 1:01:03.459
reporter:
<i>These flight attendants</i>
<i>took the unusual step</i>

1:01:03.542 --> 1:01:05.459
<i>of taking their case
right to the home</i>

1:01:05.542 --> 1:01:07.709
<i>of TWA chairman Carl Icahn.</i>

1:01:14.959 --> 1:01:17.042
I said, "Bullshit," and I went
out there with the kids.

1:01:17.125 --> 1:01:19.334
"You're not taking the kids."
I said, "I'm taking the kids."

1:01:27.834 --> 1:01:29.584
striker:
Here's the lies right here,

1:01:29.667 --> 1:01:30.959
our new work rules.

1:01:31.042 --> 1:01:34.125
(strikers complaining)

1:01:34.209 --> 1:01:36.042
Well, that's what...
this is, this is...

1:01:36.125 --> 1:01:38.083
You know, I can't...
You're being a little...

1:01:38.167 --> 1:01:40.292
-woman: Quiet, let him talk.
-Carl: You've got an airline

1:01:40.375 --> 1:01:42.500
that's losing
200 million bucks in '85

1:01:42.584 --> 1:01:44.709
and it's losing a lot
in this quarter...

1:01:44.792 --> 1:01:48.042
(strikers drowning out Icahn)

1:01:48.125 --> 1:01:49.375
'Cause we can't compete.

1:01:49.459 --> 1:01:51.542
-Can I finish?
-(strikers clamoring)

1:01:51.626 --> 1:01:53.751
You wanna listen?
You come to my home
on a Saturday,

1:01:53.834 --> 1:01:55.709
I've still
come out here to talk to you,

1:01:55.792 --> 1:01:57.459
and I want--
and I think you should
give me the courtesy

1:01:57.542 --> 1:01:59.209
to listen
as long as I'm talking to you.

1:01:59.292 --> 1:02:00.459
-man: That's fair.
-Miss Frankovich

1:02:00.542 --> 1:02:02.125
should have come
to that meeting in August,

1:02:02.209 --> 1:02:03.417
you don't like to hear it,

1:02:03.500 --> 1:02:05.083
because at that time
I could have got financing.

1:02:05.167 --> 1:02:06.334
I told her I need
three people there,

1:02:06.417 --> 1:02:07.626
she says,
"I'm going to a party,"

1:02:07.709 --> 1:02:10.459
-and that's the truth of it.
-(crowd clamoring)

1:02:10.542 --> 1:02:13.375
-I'm telling you what happened.
You don't wanna hear it.
-man: Cheap shot.

1:02:13.459 --> 1:02:16.209
-That's a cheap shot.
-Carl: Now, let me finish up.

1:02:16.292 --> 1:02:18.292
Could I? Then you can talk.
Instead of yelling.

1:02:18.375 --> 1:02:21.375
-You're brainwashed.
-man: No, we are reasonable.

1:02:21.459 --> 1:02:23.292
I mean this.
I am not here to hurt you.

1:02:23.375 --> 1:02:25.876
I think a lot of people
are getting wrong
information from her.

1:02:25.959 --> 1:02:28.042
<i>I'm getting a lot of calls from
a lot of flight attendants,</i>

1:02:28.125 --> 1:02:30.250
<i>say they'd love to come back,
they're being
intimidated by her...</i>

1:02:30.334 --> 1:02:33.042
-that they're being
scared by her.
-strikers: No!

1:02:33.125 --> 1:02:35.417
-man:<i> That's not true.</i>
-(strikers clamoring)

1:02:35.500 --> 1:02:38.459
(chuckles) That is good.

1:02:38.542 --> 1:02:41.334
Yeah, I remember that.

1:02:41.417 --> 1:02:43.626
I wanna keep that,
that's a good clip.

1:02:43.709 --> 1:02:45.292
Show that to my grandchildren.

1:02:45.375 --> 1:02:48.083
I have a whole group
that's willing to meet.
She says she wants me there.

1:02:48.167 --> 1:02:51.417
You can't force me
to like somebody, okay?
I don't like dealing with her.

1:02:51.500 --> 1:02:55.250
Okay? Because she lies.
But that doesn't mean I don't
have a whole group of people

1:02:55.334 --> 1:02:57.083
that are there
qualified to talk to her.

1:02:57.167 --> 1:02:59.751
We're willing to talk.
I don't wanna be there with her.

1:03:01.584 --> 1:03:03.000
It was sort of exciting.

1:03:03.083 --> 1:03:05.959
(strikers jeering)

1:03:06.042 --> 1:03:07.459
Carl:<i> The strikers</i>
<i>didn't understand.</i>

1:03:07.542 --> 1:03:09.042
Frankovich told them
a lot of bullshit.

1:03:09.125 --> 1:03:11.209
And a lot of them
agreed with me.

1:03:11.292 --> 1:03:13.375
After a week,
she pulled them off,

1:03:13.459 --> 1:03:15.334
she wouldn't let them come
to my house anymore

1:03:15.417 --> 1:03:17.584
'cause they were all
now complaining to her.

1:03:19.334 --> 1:03:21.626
Wapner:
<i>I don't know if Carl expected</i>

1:03:21.709 --> 1:03:24.083
that he was gonna have
this kind of turbulence

1:03:24.167 --> 1:03:25.626
right off the bat.

1:03:25.709 --> 1:03:27.083
I think he would tell you
he thought he was

1:03:27.167 --> 1:03:29.959
fighting the good fight,
and yet what he was doing

1:03:30.042 --> 1:03:32.250
played into every stereotype

1:03:32.334 --> 1:03:34.709
of the evil Wall Street
financier.

1:03:34.792 --> 1:03:37.000
The companies
that he leaves behind

1:03:37.083 --> 1:03:38.459
incur a tremendous
amount of debt

1:03:38.542 --> 1:03:40.292
and then they
start laying off,

1:03:40.375 --> 1:03:41.918
and that's more
and more Americans

1:03:42.000 --> 1:03:43.250
falling below
the poverty line.

1:03:43.334 --> 1:03:45.626
I've been seeing
a counselor since the strike

1:03:45.709 --> 1:03:48.667
because it is emotionally
devastating to have lost...

1:03:48.751 --> 1:03:50.959
I mean, I've been a flight
attendant my entire adult life.

1:03:51.042 --> 1:03:52.626
Every one
of those flight attendants

1:03:52.709 --> 1:03:55.167
could have walked across
the picket line, which many did.

1:03:55.250 --> 1:03:58.042
Many of them said,
"Hey, Vicki Frankovich,
the heck with it."

1:03:58.125 --> 1:03:59.542
They could have
kept their jobs.

1:03:59.626 --> 1:04:01.959
I didn't tell you not to cross,
we begged you to cross.

1:04:02.042 --> 1:04:03.792
We came out, we told you
over and over.

1:04:03.876 --> 1:04:05.375
They had work rules
that we couldn't afford.

1:04:05.459 --> 1:04:07.959
If I hadn't come along
and borrowed $700 million

1:04:08.042 --> 1:04:09.375
on my name,
you'd be chapter 11.

1:04:09.459 --> 1:04:11.459
If you're chapter 11,
it wouldn't do you any damn good

1:04:11.542 --> 1:04:13.834
'cause you wouldn't be working,
you'd be like Eastern.

1:04:17.667 --> 1:04:20.459
Pan Am, Eastern, and Braniff,

1:04:20.542 --> 1:04:22.876
there was a whole bunch
of them that went under.

1:04:27.792 --> 1:04:29.542
<i>And during that period,</i>

1:04:29.626 --> 1:04:32.792
we turned TWA around,
for a couple of years.

1:04:36.584 --> 1:04:39.209
announcer:
<i>The U.S. is a bargain</i>

1:04:39.292 --> 1:04:40.709
<i>if you know where to shop.</i>

1:04:40.792 --> 1:04:43.834
<i>And the best place
is today's TWA.</i>

1:04:43.918 --> 1:04:46.125
<i>We've got low air fares
to terrific cities...</i>

1:04:46.209 --> 1:04:48.834
We brought innovation
with a business saver fare.

1:04:48.918 --> 1:04:50.876
announcer:
<i>Bargains on the ground, too,</i>

1:04:50.959 --> 1:04:52.167
<i>like our travel value pack.</i>

1:04:52.250 --> 1:04:54.584
Carl:<i> We created</i>
<i>the flight attendants school.</i>

1:04:54.667 --> 1:04:56.250
<i>♪ You're gonna like us ♪</i>

1:04:56.334 --> 1:04:58.125
<i>♪ TWA ♪</i>

1:04:58.209 --> 1:05:02.500
I made mistakes with it,
though, I mean, I made
a lot of mistakes with it.

1:05:02.584 --> 1:05:05.375
<i>And then it, then it got
from bad to worse.</i>

1:05:05.459 --> 1:05:08.584
(ominous music playing)

1:05:11.500 --> 1:05:15.792
<i>♪ Happy birthday,
Dear Carl ♪</i>

1:05:15.876 --> 1:05:20.459
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you... ♪</i>

1:05:20.542 --> 1:05:22.083
The problems were endemic.

1:05:22.167 --> 1:05:24.459
People weren't traveling
to Europe for a while,

1:05:24.542 --> 1:05:26.292
you had that Desert Storm
that came.

1:05:29.375 --> 1:05:31.042
<i>There were a lot of
other things, too,</i>

1:05:31.125 --> 1:05:32.834
<i>with the terrorism.</i>

1:05:33.918 --> 1:05:35.500
He was perplexed.

1:05:35.584 --> 1:05:37.417
"Why can't I figure this out?"

1:05:40.250 --> 1:05:43.626
He's always had a magic wand.
Didn't work here.

1:05:45.083 --> 1:05:48.417
Carl eventually
took the company private,

1:05:48.500 --> 1:05:50.584
but it was loaded with debt.

1:05:53.876 --> 1:05:56.375
And TWA ended up
filing for bankruptcy.

1:06:03.334 --> 1:06:06.250
I really believe that, you know,
you look at the results,

1:06:06.334 --> 1:06:09.876
and if it doesn't work,
you blame yourself, I guess.

1:06:12.959 --> 1:06:15.334
(upbeat music playing)

1:06:15.417 --> 1:06:18.334
<i>I'm taking you back
to where I grew up.</i>

1:06:18.417 --> 1:06:20.375
<i>You've always asked me
as a little girl,</i>

1:06:20.459 --> 1:06:22.751
<i>and I'm gonna show you,
before I moved to Florida.</i>

1:06:22.834 --> 1:06:24.709
-So little...
-I've heard so many stories.

1:06:24.792 --> 1:06:26.959
So little,
but I grew up there.

1:06:27.042 --> 1:06:28.500
♪ ♪

1:06:28.584 --> 1:06:31.500
I think it wasn't...
